Predicting the Age of Amur Tigers

Shonda Kuiper

1. Introduction

The Bolshaya Koshka (Russian for big cat) Reserve is a newly created animal reserve that was uniquely developed to help endangered species prosper. This 10,000 acre wild animal reservation was selected because an abundance of Siberian tigers have been found in the area. The diverse terrain of the reserve provides a wide variety of habitats for many different species of animals.

Since the tigers in this area are much more abundant than any other area in the world, they are starting to draw a significant number of researchers to the region. Your primary responsibility will be to help these researchers as they study the tigers and then incorporate the results of their research into a system to identify the best management practices for this reserve.

An important component of monitoring endangered species is to understand the age distribution of the population. At this preliminary stage, you you will examine the preliminary tiger data collected to determine if it is appropriate to use in developing a model for tiger age prediction and potentially other research questions of interest. Your Tiger1 dataset contains several variables:

  • Age (in years) - a quantitative variable that ranges from 0 to 20
  • NoseBlack - the percent of the tigers nose that is black
  • Weight (in pounds)
  • Sex (Female or Male)
  • Length - the length of the tiger (in inches)
  • Paw - the width of the back paw (in inches)
  • Region - one of 6 regions of the preserve (0, 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5) defined by terrain features

Addressing Issues of Potential Bias

Based on the results and observations made in Section 2, you likely noticed that different populations of tigers tend to live in different reasons. For example, it appears that some regions have a much larger percentage of female tigers than others.

  • Is this sample representative of the tiger population more generally? If not, why? If so, give support for this answer.
  • Would your sample be appropriate for answering questions like estimating the average size or age of tigers in the preserve?
  • If another sample were taken, what recommendations would you make for collecting the data? Are there dangers with simply randomly walking around and collecting data on the closest tigers?

A final note about random sampling and bias: all is not lost if a sample has issues such as regional differences, or data that differs on some other characteristic between comparison groups. Sometimes, more complicated models can account for or adjust for these disparities. A multivariable model, for example, might suffice. Of course, a better option is to carefully plan the sampling to ensure bias is not present. A simple random sample is not always best and other sampling schemes are possible. Review additional statistical studies or consult a statistician prior to collecting or analyzing data that could have these issues.

3. Creating a Model to Predict Age

You may have noticed that in the previous graphs that measures of size (Length, Paw, and Weight) are very helpful for predicting a tigers age when they are young (such as less than 3 years old), but these variables are not very useful when a tiger is older.

Let use a simple linear regression model to predict Age based upon Weight.

Tiger.lm = lm(Age ~ Weight, data = Tiger1)  # Creating a simple linear model

In this article, the subscript in Table 1 states, Predicted values are based upon the least-squares regression of a truncated data set for 63 known-aged females in the Serengeti and Ngorongoro aged \(\leq\) 10 yr (Age = 2.0667 + 5.9037arcsin(NoseBlack); \(r^2 = 0.75\), \(p \leq 0.0001\)).

7. How to build a model

Building a model is both a science and an art, and there is no substitute for experience. But beginners need some guidelines to help them develop experiences more efficiently. Suppose we are modeling how \(y\) depends on some potential predictors \(x_1, x_2, \dots\).

Is there theory to support a particular model?

Sometimes we have good theoretical reasons to expect (or at least wonder about) a particular type of relationship. If so, we should let that guide our model building.

When we are less informed by a particular theory, we can answer the following questions to help guide us toward a model.

Should I include a constant term (intercept) in the model?

Usually the answer to this is yes. Certainly it is a good place to start. It is a pretty strong (and often clearly false) assumption that the response variable should be zero when all the predictors are 0.

Should I include (a transformation of) \(x_i\) in the model?

If it seems like \(y\) might depend on \(x_i\), then \(x_i\) is a candidate for inclusion. [A tranformation of a variable \(x_i\) is just another variable, so it isnt really a special case. But often transformed versions of the natural or available variables improves the model.]

Should I include \(x_i^2\) (quadratic term) in the model?

The main purpose of a quadratic term is not turn a line into a curve (transformations also do that) but to turn a monotonic function into a function with an optimum. If we expect that there is a value of \(x_i\) that makes \(y\) largest (or smallest), we should consider including a quadratic term.

Should I include \(x_i x_j\) (interaction term) in the model?

If how why depends on \(x_i\) depends on the value of \(x_j\), then an interaction term is warranted. In particular, if we have used \(x_i^2\) and the value of \(x_i\) that makes \(y\) largest (or smallest) depends on \(x_j\), then we should include an interaction term.

Example

How does the speed at which a bicyclist can ride a bicycle depend on

  • gear ratio (\(g\))
  • steepness of the road (\(s\))

Both variables seem likely to affect the speed, so we include \(g\) and \(s\) (and an intercept) in the model.

If the gear ratio is too high or too low, the bicyclist cannot go as fast, so we should include a quadratic term for \(g\). For any steepness, their is an optimal gear ratio.

Furthermore, the optimal gear ratio depends on the steepness (thats we we make bicycles with multiple gear ratios). So we should include an interaction term.

But we dont need a quadratic term for \(s\) since the speed is monotonic in steepness. (If it were not, as hill got steeper and steeper, we would go slower and slower until they got really steep, when we would start going faster again.)
